This can improve optimization as there are more patterns about Reshape. For example,

```python
layer = tf.keras.layers.MultiHeadAttention(num_heads=3, key_dim=5)
target = tf.keras.Input(shape=[8, 16], batch_size=1)
source = tf.keras.Input(shape=[4, 16], batch_size=1)
output_tensor = layer(target, source, return_attention_scores=False)
model = tf.keras.Model([target, source], output_tensor)
```

Converting Pack to Reshape can help the bias of the last EinsumDense fused into FullyConnected.

[{"sha":"c6ce62e442ff1e82342b68c101e9f350ae516d7f","author":{"name":"Tzu-Wei Sung","email":"f316c63976b7dfc02c6169d1441ce0da0786fcb6@gmail.com"},"message":"Convert Pack to Reshape when there is only one operand to be packed.

This can improve optimization as there are more patterns about Reshape. For example,

```python
layer = tf.keras.layers.MultiHeadAttention(num_heads=3, key_dim=5)
target = tf.keras.Input(shape=[8, 16], batch_size=1)
source = tf.keras.Input(shape=[4, 16], batch_size=1)
output_tensor = layer(target, source, return_attention_scores=False)
model = tf.keras.Model([target, source], output_tensor)
```

Converting Pack to Reshape can help the bias of the last EinsumDense fused into FullyConnected.

layer = tf.keras.layers.MultiHeadAttention(num_heads=3, key_dim=5)

[{"sha":"8981e41c2b3db99d10721e6d419241d98c5caa70","author":{"name":"Scott Tseng","email":"a1ff4dd2b5a82ce8bba2b04d40eec6d4c3e5ccbb@nlptech.com"},"message":"Fix a bug where reordering tf.Transpose is not done correctly","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/KabirKwatra/tensorflow/commits/8981e41c2b3db99d10721e6d419241d98c5caa70"},{"sha":"c6ce62e442ff1e82342b68c101e9f350ae516d7f","author":{"name":"Tzu-Wei Sung","email":"f316c63976b7dfc02c6169d1441ce0da0786fcb6@gmail.com"},"message":"Convert Pack to Reshape when there is only one operand to be packed.

This can improve optimization as there are more patterns about Reshape. For example,

```python
layer = tf.keras.layers.MultiHeadAttention(num_heads=3, key_dim=5)
target = tf.keras.Input(shape=[8, 16], batch_size=1)
source = tf.keras.Input(shape=[4, 16], batch_size=1)
output_tensor = layer(target, source, return_attention_scores=False)
model = tf.keras.Model([target, source], output_tensor)
```

Converting Pack to Reshape can help the bias of the last EinsumDense fused into FullyConnected.

[{"sha":"c6ce62e442ff1e82342b68c101e9f350ae516d7f","author":{"name":"Tzu-Wei Sung","email":"f316c63976b7dfc02c6169d1441ce0da0786fcb6@gmail.com"},"message":"Convert Pack to Reshape when there is only one operand to be packed.

This can improve optimization as there are more patterns about Reshape. For example,

```python
layer = tf.keras.layers.MultiHeadAttention(num_heads=3, key_dim=5)
target = tf.keras.Input(shape=[8, 16], batch_size=1)
source = tf.keras.Input(shape=[4, 16], batch_size=1)
output_tensor = layer(target, source, return_attention_scores=False)
model = tf.keras.Model([target, source], output_tensor)
```

Converting Pack to Reshape can help the bias of the last EinsumDense fused into FullyConnected.

[{"sha":"c6ce62e442ff1e82342b68c101e9f350ae516d7f","author":{"name":"Tzu-Wei Sung","email":"f316c63976b7dfc02c6169d1441ce0da0786fcb6@gmail.com"},"message":"Convert Pack to Reshape when there is only one operand to be packed.

This can improve optimization as there are more patterns about Reshape. For example,

```python
layer = tf.keras.layers.MultiHeadAttention(num_heads=3, key_dim=5)
target = tf.keras.Input(shape=[8, 16], batch_size=1)
source = tf.keras.Input(shape=[4, 16], batch_size=1)
output_tensor = layer(target, source, return_attention_scores=False)
model = tf.keras.Model([target, source], output_tensor)
```

Converting Pack to Reshape can help the bias of the last EinsumDense fused into FullyConnected.

This can improve optimization as there are more patterns about Reshape. For example,

```python
layer = tf.keras.layers.MultiHeadAttention(num_heads=3, key_dim=5)
target = tf.keras.Input(shape=[8, 16], batch_size=1)
source = tf.keras.Input(shape=[4, 16], batch_size=1)
output_tensor = layer(target, source, return_attention_scores=False)
model = tf.keras.Model([target, source], output_tensor)
```

Converting Pack to Reshape can help the bias of the last EinsumDense fused into FullyConnected.

* Move traversal logic to ReactFiberCommitWork

The current traversal logic is spread between ReactFiberWorkLoop and
ReactFiberCommitWork, and it's a bit awkward, especially when
refactoring. Idk the ideal module structure, so for now I'd rather keep
it all in one file.

* Traverse commit phase effects iteratively

We suspect that using the JS stack to traverse through the tree in the
commit phase is slower than traversing iteratively.

I've kept the recursive implementation behind a flag, both so we have
the option to run an experiment comparing the two, and so we can revert
it easily later if needed.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/trueadm/react/commits/25b18d31c8b7ffd256416672dc21c50dd22ac3dc"},{"sha":"779a472b0901b2d28e382f3850b2ad09a555b014","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Prevent inlining into recursive commit functions (#20105)

Adds a bunch of no-inline directives to commit phase functions to
prevent them from being inlined into one of our recursive algorithms.

The motivation is to minimize the number of variables in the recursive
functions, since each one contributes to the size of the stack frame.

Theoretically, this could help the performance of both the recursive
and non-recursive (iterative) implementations of the commit phase,
since even the iterative implementation sometimes uses the JS stack.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/trueadm/react/commits/779a472b0901b2d28e382f3850b2ad09a555b014"},{"sha":"b6a750be3ca0fc4126ef018e205c951b890c1881","author":{"name":"Brian Vaughn","email":"59942a8ec08225673b377c556396ca24baabd1b2@fb.com"},"message":"Make DevTools Websocket retry delay configurable (#20107)","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/trueadm/react/commits/b6a750be3ca0fc4126ef018e205c951b890c1881"},{"sha":"343d7a4a7eb621a31ba946309b557e0988be3a63","author":{"name":"Brian Vaughn","email":"59942a8ec08225673b377c556396ca24baabd1b2@fb.com"},"message":"Fast Refresh: Don't block DevTools commit hook (#20129)

This exposes a host environment (bundler) specific hook to check if an
object is a module reference. This will be used so that they can be passed
directly into Flight without needing additional wrapper objects.

* Emit module references as a special type of value

We already have JSON and errors as special types of "rows". This encodes
module references as a special type of row value. This was always the
intention because it allows those values to be emitted first in the stream
so that as a large models stream down, we can start preloading as early
as possible.

We preload the module when they resolve but we lazily require them as they
are referenced.

* Emit module references where ever they occur

This emits module references where ever they occur. In blocks or even
directly in elements.

* Don't special case the root row

I originally did this so that a simple stream is also just plain JSON.

However, since we might want to emit things like modules before the root
module in the stream, this gets unnecessarily complicated. We could add
this back as a special case if it's the first byte written but meh.

Since Flight now accepts a module reference as returned by any bundler
system, depending on the renderer running. We need to drastically relax
the check to include all of them. We can add more as we discover them.

* Move flow annotation

Seems like our compiler is not happy with stripping this.

This should avoid having to list all transitive dependencies in every
invocation of gentbl and enable much nicer includes specification. This
is designed to allow a drop-in replacement to ease transition to the
new functionality. All existing usages of gentbl should also work with
this rule. I tested out fully transitioning the current build rules to
use td_library, but am going to submit this as just the change to
the rule, with the BUILD file changes coming later to make things more
incremental.

[{"sha":"e305de966248fe0f926739ee337ce8c17e24948a","author":{"name":"Smit Hinsu","email":"0f9dce5f2da36d8473ff9a50fbb0e06a148c5fae@google.com"},"message":"Add an option to export entry function to function library

Currently, main function is added to the given Graph and other functions are added to the function library. That's not desirable if we want to export MLIR module that was imported from a function.

This change introduces a way to invert ConvertFunctionToMlir function.

This is required to fall back to the old bridge for second phase of the compilation.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 360405556
Change-Id: I885e0a7cab3555946a8f2d39e9640ec28d9d653f","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/osmaelo/tensorflow/commits/bf6f03809ef73105c31734ff9b750902ea57d88e"},{"sha":"8f9e5f03d19d6b5df6c009ced2ce44e45674255d","author":{"name":"Jean-Baptiste Lespiau","email":"d3229a97a8a1a3969929b7309247ec1d345f5156@google.com"},"message":"Remove a callback to Python to get the value of some flag.

This is done to simplify the code, and not at all for performance, because it's only executed during the compilation phase.

One possible design question: should we let the user access the value of the flag if it has not been set? Right now, the Python code allows it I think (meaning the behavior may not match the flag value, which has not been parsed yet).
We could raise an error, by setting the flag value to absl::nullopt, and check it's not null. But it would be a breaking change, so I am a little reluctant doing so.

[{"sha":"e305de966248fe0f926739ee337ce8c17e24948a","author":{"name":"Smit Hinsu","email":"0f9dce5f2da36d8473ff9a50fbb0e06a148c5fae@google.com"},"message":"Add an option to export entry function to function library

Currently, main function is added to the given Graph and other functions are added to the function library. That's not desirable if we want to export MLIR module that was imported from a function.

This change introduces a way to invert ConvertFunctionToMlir function.

This is required to fall back to the old bridge for second phase of the compilation.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 360405556
Change-Id: I885e0a7cab3555946a8f2d39e9640ec28d9d653f","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Cache-Cloud/tensorflow/commits/bf6f03809ef73105c31734ff9b750902ea57d88e"},{"sha":"8f9e5f03d19d6b5df6c009ced2ce44e45674255d","author":{"name":"Jean-Baptiste Lespiau","email":"d3229a97a8a1a3969929b7309247ec1d345f5156@google.com"},"message":"Remove a callback to Python to get the value of some flag.

This is done to simplify the code, and not at all for performance, because it's only executed during the compilation phase.

We could raise an error, by setting the flag value to absl::nullopt, and check it's not null. But it would be a breaking change, so I am a little reluctant doing so.

[{"sha":"c6ce62e442ff1e82342b68c101e9f350ae516d7f","author":{"name":"Tzu-Wei Sung","email":"f316c63976b7dfc02c6169d1441ce0da0786fcb6@gmail.com"},"message":"Convert Pack to Reshape when there is only one operand to be packed.

This can improve optimization as there are more patterns about Reshape. For example,

```python
layer = tf.keras.layers.MultiHeadAttention(num_heads=3, key_dim=5)
target = tf.keras.Input(shape=[8, 16], batch_size=1)
source = tf.keras.Input(shape=[4, 16], batch_size=1)
output_tensor = layer(target, source, return_attention_scores=False)
model = tf.keras.Model([target, source], output_tensor)
```

Converting Pack to Reshape can help the bias of the last EinsumDense fused into FullyConnected.

This can improve optimization as there are more patterns about Reshape. For example,

```python
layer = tf.keras.layers.MultiHeadAttention(num_heads=3, key_dim=5)

```

Converting Pack to Reshape can help the bias of the last EinsumDense fused into FullyConnected.

[{"sha":"e305de966248fe0f926739ee337ce8c17e24948a","author":{"name":"Smit Hinsu","email":"0f9dce5f2da36d8473ff9a50fbb0e06a148c5fae@google.com"},"message":"Add an option to export entry function to function library

Currently, main function is added to the given Graph and other functions are added to the function library. That's not desirable if we want to export MLIR module that was imported from a function.

This change introduces a way to invert ConvertFunctionToMlir function.

This is required to fall back to the old bridge for second phase of the compilation.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 360405556
Change-Id: I885e0a7cab3555946a8f2d39e9640ec28d9d653f","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Mu-L/tensorflow/commits/bf6f03809ef73105c31734ff9b750902ea57d88e"},{"sha":"8f9e5f03d19d6b5df6c009ced2ce44e45674255d","author":{"name":"Jean-Baptiste Lespiau","email":"d3229a97a8a1a3969929b7309247ec1d345f5156@google.com"},"message":"Remove a callback to Python to get the value of some flag.

This is done to simplify the code, and not at all for performance, because it's only executed during the compilation phase.

One possible design question: should we let the user access the value of the flag if it has not been set? Right now, the Python code allows it I think (meaning the behavior may not match the flag value, which has not been parsed yet).
We could raise an error, by setting the flag value to absl::nullopt, and check it's not null. But it would be a breaking change, so I am a little reluctant doing so.

[{"sha":"e305de966248fe0f926739ee337ce8c17e24948a","author":{"name":"Smit Hinsu","email":"0f9dce5f2da36d8473ff9a50fbb0e06a148c5fae@google.com"},"message":"Add an option to export entry function to function library

Currently, main function is added to the given Graph and other functions are added to the function library. That's not desirable if we want to export MLIR module that was imported from a function.

This change introduces a way to invert ConvertFunctionToMlir function.

This is required to fall back to the old bridge for second phase of the compilation.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 360405556
Change-Id: I885e0a7cab3555946a8f2d39e9640ec28d9d653f","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/njzjz/tensorflow/commits/bf6f03809ef73105c31734ff9b750902ea57d88e"},{"sha":"8f9e5f03d19d6b5df6c009ced2ce44e45674255d","author":{"name":"Jean-Baptiste Lespiau","email":"d3229a97a8a1a3969929b7309247ec1d345f5156@google.com"},"message":"Remove a callback to Python to get the value of some flag.

This is done to simplify the code, and not at all for performance, because it's only executed during the compilation phase.

One possible design question: should we let the user access the value of the flag if it has not been set? Right now, the Python code allows it I think (meaning the behavior may not match the flag value, which has not been parsed yet).
We could raise an error, by setting the flag value to absl::nullopt, and check it's not null. But it would be a breaking change, so I am a little reluctant doing so.

[{"sha":"e305de966248fe0f926739ee337ce8c17e24948a","author":{"name":"Smit Hinsu","email":"0f9dce5f2da36d8473ff9a50fbb0e06a148c5fae@google.com"},"message":"Add an option to export entry function to function library

Currently, main function is added to the given Graph and other functions are added to the function library. That's not desirable if we want to export MLIR module that was imported from a function.

This change introduces a way to invert ConvertFunctionToMlir function.

This is required to fall back to the old bridge for second phase of the compilation.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 360405556
Change-Id: I885e0a7cab3555946a8f2d39e9640ec28d9d653f","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/KaycoinsInc/tensorflow/commits/bf6f03809ef73105c31734ff9b750902ea57d88e"},{"sha":"8f9e5f03d19d6b5df6c009ced2ce44e45674255d","author":{"name":"Jean-Baptiste Lespiau","email":"d3229a97a8a1a3969929b7309247ec1d345f5156@google.com"},"message":"Remove a callback to Python to get the value of some flag.

This is done to simplify the code, and not at all for performance, because it's only executed during the compilation phase.

One possible design question: should we let the user access the value of the flag if it has not been set? Right now, the Python code allows it I think (meaning the behavior may not match the flag value, which has not been parsed yet).
We could raise an error, by setting the flag value to absl::nullopt, and check it's not null. But it would be a breaking change, so I am a little reluctant doing so.

incremental.

[{"sha":"042699b08ec3177b052da945cdbfda20ff84f7bf","author":{"name":"Haoliang Zhang","email":"0ed73abe53b90931ec96009f1753190a42740aac@google.com"},"message":"Apply several fixes to the dilated conv pass:
1) Consider the value in `PadOp` to determine the result padding scheme for Conv2D. If PadOp doesn't wrap a constant value, then we should reject the pattern to be safe.
2) If `paddings` or `crops` are non-constant, or don't have same shape, then reject the pattern.
3) Fix places in the mlir tests where `padding` or `crops` are non-constant.
4) Report match errors via `notifyMatchFailures` throughout the pass to give better debug information during legalization failure.

[{"sha":"cb58fbae7070eab1a58a76ef26eb439b8ec34d6d","author":{"name":"Prakalp Srivastava","email":"7da1985d121fd79537822bb42be62798d2d2aa23@google.com"},"message":"Keep track of visited functions during export using a Set during MLIR to Graph export.

ConvertLibFunction checks if the requested function has already been exported by first creating a FunctionLibraryDefinition (map between function name and function def) and then querying it with function name. Since we immediately discard this FunctionLibraryDefinition, we incur the creation and destruction cost of FunctionLibraryDefinition each time we export a function. Using a set to keep track of visited functions is much less expensive.

[{"sha":"e305de966248fe0f926739ee337ce8c17e24948a","author":{"name":"Smit Hinsu","email":"0f9dce5f2da36d8473ff9a50fbb0e06a148c5fae@google.com"},"message":"Add an option to export entry function to function library

Currently, main function is added to the given Graph and other functions are added to the function library. That's not desirable if we want to export MLIR module that was imported from a function.

This change introduces a way to invert ConvertFunctionToMlir function.

This is required to fall back to the old bridge for second phase of the compilation.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 360398279
Change-Id: I7eaef32349c4b69c8eb3d0bfb929916794e34fc3","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/isanjit3/tensorflow/commits/e305de966248fe0f926739ee337ce8c17e24948a"},{"sha":"bf6f03809ef73105c31734ff9b750902ea57d88e","author":{"name":"Smit Hinsu","email":"0f9dce5f2da36d8473ff9a50fbb0e06a148c5fae@google.com"},"message":"Define helper function for effective MlirBridgeRollout enum

This decides the effective rollout based on ConfigProto and flags. Planning to use this from _TpuCompileMlir op to fallback to the old bridge if safe mode is enabled.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 360405556
Change-Id: I885e0a7cab3555946a8f2d39e9640ec28d9d653f","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/isanjit3/tensorflow/commits/bf6f03809ef73105c31734ff9b750902ea57d88e"},{"sha":"8f9e5f03d19d6b5df6c009ced2ce44e45674255d","author":{"name":"Jean-Baptiste Lespiau","email":"d3229a97a8a1a3969929b7309247ec1d345f5156@google.com"},"message":"Remove a callback to Python to get the value of some flag.

This is done to simplify the code, and not at all for performance, because it's only executed during the compilation phase.

One possible design question: should we let the user access the value of the flag if it has not been set? Right now, the Python code allows it I think (meaning the behavior may not match the flag value, which has not been parsed yet).
We could raise an error, by setting the flag value to absl::nullopt, and check it's not null. But it would be a breaking change, so I am a little reluctant doing so.

[{"sha":"e305de966248fe0f926739ee337ce8c17e24948a","author":{"name":"Smit Hinsu","email":"0f9dce5f2da36d8473ff9a50fbb0e06a148c5fae@google.com"},"message":"Add an option to export entry function to function library

Currently, main function is added to the given Graph and other functions are added to the function library. That's not desirable if we want to export MLIR module that was imported from a function.

This change introduces a way to invert ConvertFunctionToMlir function.

This is required to fall back to the old bridge for second phase of the compilation.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 360398279
Change-Id: I7eaef32349c4b69c8eb3d0bfb929916794e34fc3","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Rachelmorrell/tensorflow/commits/e305de966248fe0f926739ee337ce8c17e24948a"},{"sha":"bf6f03809ef73105c31734ff9b750902ea57d88e","author":{"name":"Smit Hinsu","email":"0f9dce5f2da36d8473ff9a50fbb0e06a148c5fae@google.com"},"message":"Define helper function for effective MlirBridgeRollout enum

This decides the effective rollout based on ConfigProto and flags. Planning to use this from _TpuCompileMlir op to fallback to the old bridge if safe mode is enabled.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 360405556
Change-Id: I885e0a7cab3555946a8f2d39e9640ec28d9d653f","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Rachelmorrell/tensorflow/commits/bf6f03809ef73105c31734ff9b750902ea57d88e"},{"sha":"8f9e5f03d19d6b5df6c009ced2ce44e45674255d","author":{"name":"Jean-Baptiste Lespiau","email":"d3229a97a8a1a3969929b7309247ec1d345f5156@google.com"},"message":"Remove a callback to Python to get the value of some flag.

This is done to simplify the code, and not at all for performance, because it's only executed during the compilation phase.

One possible design question: should we let the user access the value of the flag if it has not been set? Right now, the Python code allows it I think (meaning the behavior may not match the flag value, which has not been parsed yet).
We could raise an error, by setting the flag value to absl::nullopt, and check it's not null. But it would be a breaking change, so I am a little reluctant doing so.

This should avoid having to list all transitive dependencies in every
invocation of gentbl and enable much nicer includes specification. This
is designed to allow a drop-in replacement to ease transition to the
new functionality. All existing usages of gentbl should also work with
this rule. I tested out fully transitioning the current build rules to
use td_library, but am going to submit this as just the change to
the rule, with the BUILD file changes coming later to make things more
incremental.

[{"sha":"e305de966248fe0f926739ee337ce8c17e24948a","author":{"name":"Smit Hinsu","email":"0f9dce5f2da36d8473ff9a50fbb0e06a148c5fae@google.com"},"message":"Add an option to export entry function to function library

Currently, main function is added to the given Graph and other functions are added to the function library. That's not desirable if we want to export MLIR module that was imported from a function.

This is required to fall back to the old bridge for second phase of the compilation.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 360405556
Change-Id: I885e0a7cab3555946a8f2d39e9640ec28d9d653f","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/icpm/tensorflow/commits/bf6f03809ef73105c31734ff9b750902ea57d88e"},{"sha":"8f9e5f03d19d6b5df6c009ced2ce44e45674255d","author":{"name":"Jean-Baptiste Lespiau","email":"d3229a97a8a1a3969929b7309247ec1d345f5156@google.com"},"message":"Remove a callback to Python to get the value of some flag.

This is done to simplify the code, and not at all for performance, because it's only executed during the compilation phase.

One possible design question: should we let the user access the value of the flag if it has not been set? Right now, the Python code allows it I think (meaning the behavior may not match the flag value, which has not been parsed yet).
We could raise an error, by setting the flag value to absl::nullopt, and check it's not null. But it would be a breaking change, so I am a little reluctant doing so.

[{"sha":"e305de966248fe0f926739ee337ce8c17e24948a","author":{"name":"Smit Hinsu","email":"0f9dce5f2da36d8473ff9a50fbb0e06a148c5fae@google.com"},"message":"Add an option to export entry function to function library

Currently, main function is added to the given Graph and other functions are added to the function library. That's not desirable if we want to export MLIR module that was imported from a function.

This change introduces a way to invert ConvertFunctionToMlir function.

This reverts commit 553440bd1578ef71982c4a10e2cc8c462f33d9be.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/acdlite/react/commits/ee432635724d5a50301448016caa137ac3c0a7a2"},{"sha":"cfcabda6d100dd1a0749c60333df8ffcbb715c62","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Move context comparison to consumer

In the lazy context implementation, not all context changes are
propagated from the provider, so we can't rely on the propagation alone
to mark the consumer as dirty. The consumer needs to compare to the
previous value, like we do for state and context.

I added a `memoizedValue` field to the context dependency type. Then in
the consumer, we iterate over the current dependencies to see if
something changed. We only do this iteration after props and state has
already bailed out, so it's a relatively uncommon path, except at the
root of a changed subtree. Alternatively, we could move these
comparisons into `readContext`, but that's a much hotter path, so I
think this is an appropriate trade off.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/acdlite/react/commits/cfcabda6d100dd1a0749c60333df8ffcbb715c62"},{"sha":"06a0d9e6625f3421c004e42874c89b2fc62802b8","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"[Experiment] Lazily propagate context changes

When a context provider changes, we scan the tree for matching consumers
and mark them as dirty so that we know they have pending work. This
prevents us from bailing out if, say, an intermediate wrapper is
memoized.

Currently, we propagate these changes eagerly, at the provider.

However, in many cases, we would have ended up visiting the consumer
nodes anyway, as part of the normal render traversal, because there's no
memoized node in between that bails out.

We can save CPU cycles by propagating changes only when we hit a
memoized component — so, instead of propagating eagerly at the provider,
we propagate lazily if or when something bails out.

Most of our bailout logic is centralized in
`bailoutOnAlreadyFinishedWork`, so this ended up being not that
difficult to implement correctly.

There are some exceptions: Suspense and Offscreen. Those are special
because they sometimes defer the rendering of their children to a
completely separate render cycle. In those cases, we must take extra
care to propagate *all* the context changes, not just the first one.

I'm pleasantly surprised at how little I needed to change in this
initial implementation. I was worried I'd have to use the reconciler
fork, but I ended up being able to wrap all my changes in a regular
feature flag. So, we could run an experiment in parallel to our other
ones.

I do consider this a risky rollout overall because of the potential for
subtle semantic deviations. However, the model is simple enough that I
don't expect us to have trouble fixing regressions if or when they arise
during internal dogfooding.

---

This is largely based on [RFC#118](https://github.com/reactjs/rfcs/pull/118),
by @gnoff. I did deviate in some of the implementation details, though.

The main one is how I chose to track context changes. Instead of storing
a dirty flag on the stack, I added a `memoizedValue` field to the
context dependency object. Then, to check if something has changed, the
consumer compares the new context value to the old (memoized) one.

This is necessary because of Suspense and Offscreen — those components
defer work from one render into a later one. When the subtree continues
rendering, the stack from the previous render is no longer available.
But the memoized values on the dependencies list are. This requires a
bit more work when a consumer bails out, but nothing considerable, and
there are ways we could optimize it even further. Conceptually, this
model is really appealing, since it matches how our other features
"reactively" detect changes — `useMemo`, `useEffect`,
`getDerivedStateFromProps`, the built-in cache, and so on.

I also intentionally dropped support for
`unstable_calculateChangedBits`. We're planning to remove this API
anyway before the next major release, in favor of context selectors.
It's an unstable feature that we never advertised; I don't think it's
seen much adoption.

Co-Authored-By: Josh Story <jcs.gnoff@gmail.com>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/acdlite/react/commits/06a0d9e6625f3421c004e42874c89b2fc62802b8"},{"sha":"43c60de74aad9d5675200ebf1acaecbf075de21a","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Propagate all contexts in single pass

Instead of propagating the tree once per changed context, we can check
all the contexts in a single propagation. This inverts the two loops so
that the faster loop (O(numberOfContexts)) is inside the more expensive
loop (O(numberOfFibers * avgContextDepsPerFiber)).

This adds a bit of overhead to the case where only a single context
changes because you have to unwrap the context from the array. I'm also
unsure if this will hurt cache locality.

Co-Authored-By: Josh Story <jcs.gnoff@gmail.com>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/acdlite/react/commits/43c60de74aad9d5675200ebf1acaecbf075de21a"},{"sha":"8ff55938088568e5d91a5678ad14025192160591","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Stop propagating at nearest dependency match

Because we now propagate all context providers in a single traversal, we
can defer context propagation to a subtree without losing information
about which context providers we're deferring — it's all of them.

Theoretically, this is a big optimization because it means we'll never
propagate to any tree that has work scheduled on it, nor will we ever
propagate the same tree twice.

There's an awkward case related to bailing out of the siblings of a
context consumer. Because those siblings don't bail out until after
they've already entered the begin phase, we have to do extra work to
make sure they don't unecessarily propagate context again. We could
avoid this by adding an earlier bailout for sibling nodes, something
we've discussed in the past. We should consider this during the next
refactor of the fiber tree structure.

Co-Authored-By: Josh Story <jcs.gnoff@gmail.com>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/acdlite/react/commits/8ff55938088568e5d91a5678ad14025192160591"},{"sha":"d1bfb29fa9ecd1a09163cafbaf530a3673b27336","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Mark trees that need propagation in readContext

Instead of storing matched context consumers in a Set, we can mark
when a consumer receives an update inside `readContext`.

I hesistated to put anything in this function because it's such a hot
path, but so are bail outs. Fortunately, we only need to set this flag
once, the first time a context is read. So I think it's a reasonable
trade off.

In exchange, propagation is faster because we no longer need to
accumulate a Set of matched consumers, and fiber bailouts are faster
because we don't need to consult that Set. And the code is simpler.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/acdlite/react/commits/d1bfb29fa9ecd1a09163cafbaf530a3673b27336"}]

invocation of gentbl and enable much nicer includes specification. This

the rule, with the BUILD file changes coming later to make things more
incremental.

Change-Id: I23c5b452869f772ad61a166253d1f6d4b4a508cc","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/UofT-EcoSystem/tensorflow/commits/b6f149d84ca077d825c65e61f26d5308cac02d0c"},{"sha":"cb58fbae7070eab1a58a76ef26eb439b8ec34d6d","author":{"name":"Prakalp Srivastava","email":"7da1985d121fd79537822bb42be62798d2d2aa23@google.com"},"message":"Keep track of visited functions during export using a Set during MLIR to Graph export.

ConvertLibFunction checks if the requested function has already been exported by first creating a FunctionLibraryDefinition (map between function name and function def) and then querying it with function name. Since we immediately discard this FunctionLibraryDefinition, we incur the creation and destruction cost of FunctionLibraryDefinition each time we export a function. Using a set to keep track of visited functions is much less expensive.

[{"sha":"00d31f1d50c3ef475d8301f70ffbf0647038f53f","author":{"name":"Peter Hawkins","email":"34b19541630131950b5f204f2c5f2c647a3a7475@google.com"},"message":"[XLA] Fix interface contract of xla::LogDet.

xla::LogDet was previously mixing the sign of the determinant with the sign of the logarithm. These semantics don't make sense.

Create two methods: xla::SLogDet() which returns a (sign, determinant) pair, and xla::LogDet() which returns the log-determinant for matrices with positive determinant, and NaN otherwise.

The semantics of xla::LogDet() match torch.logdet, and PyTorch/XLA is the only user of this function at the moment.

Change-Id: I23c5b452869f772ad61a166253d1f6d4b4a508cc","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/mark0725/tensorflow/commits/b6f149d84ca077d825c65e61f26d5308cac02d0c"},{"sha":"cb58fbae7070eab1a58a76ef26eb439b8ec34d6d","author":{"name":"Prakalp Srivastava","email":"7da1985d121fd79537822bb42be62798d2d2aa23@google.com"},"message":"Keep track of visited functions during export using a Set during MLIR to Graph export.

ConvertLibFunction checks if the requested function has already been exported by first creating a FunctionLibraryDefinition (map between function name and function def) and then querying it with function name. Since we immediately discard this FunctionLibraryDefinition, we incur the creation and destruction cost of FunctionLibraryDefinition each time we export a function. Using a set to keep track of visited functions is much less expensive.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 360476511
Change-Id: Ia0fb5837397143729f80e14f4421e829a2a02a1e","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/mark0725/tensorflow/commits/cb58fbae7070eab1a58a76ef26eb439b8ec34d6d"},{"sha":"042699b08ec3177b052da945cdbfda20ff84f7bf","author":{"name":"Haoliang Zhang","email":"0ed73abe53b90931ec96009f1753190a42740aac@google.com"},"message":"Apply several fixes to the dilated conv pass:
1) Consider the value in `PadOp` to determine the result padding scheme for Conv2D. If PadOp doesn't wrap a constant value, then we should reject the pattern to be safe.
2) If `paddings` or `crops` are non-constant, or don't have same shape, then reject the pattern.
3) Fix places in the mlir tests where `padding` or `crops` are non-constant.
4) Report match errors via `notifyMatchFailures` throughout the pass to give better debug information during legalization failure.

Change-Id: I9dd09bbd31bfe83b8040d06f147690e314cf9aca","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/mark0725/tensorflow/commits/7f8f4fe39bc1908e52ccb285f42fb60b7f380d7e"},{"sha":"00d31f1d50c3ef475d8301f70ffbf0647038f53f","author":{"name":"Peter Hawkins","email":"34b19541630131950b5f204f2c5f2c647a3a7475@google.com"},"message":"[XLA] Fix interface contract of xla::LogDet.

xla::LogDet was previously mixing the sign of the determinant with the sign of the logarithm. These semantics don't make sense.

Create two methods: xla::SLogDet() which returns a (sign, determinant) pair, and xla::LogDet() which returns the log-determinant for matrices with positive determinant, and NaN otherwise.

The semantics of xla::LogDet() match torch.logdet, and PyTorch/XLA is the only user of this function at the moment.

Change-Id: I23c5b452869f772ad61a166253d1f6d4b4a508cc","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Manas1820/tensorflow/commits/b6f149d84ca077d825c65e61f26d5308cac02d0c"},{"sha":"cb58fbae7070eab1a58a76ef26eb439b8ec34d6d","author":{"name":"Prakalp Srivastava","email":"7da1985d121fd79537822bb42be62798d2d2aa23@google.com"},"message":"Keep track of visited functions during export using a Set during MLIR to Graph export.

ConvertLibFunction checks if the requested function has already been exported by first creating a FunctionLibraryDefinition (map between function name and function def) and then querying it with function name. Since we immediately discard this FunctionLibraryDefinition, we incur the creation and destruction cost of FunctionLibraryDefinition each time we export a function. Using a set to keep track of visited functions is much less expensive.

Change-Id: I9dd09bbd31bfe83b8040d06f147690e314cf9aca","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Manas1820/tensorflow/commits/7f8f4fe39bc1908e52ccb285f42fb60b7f380d7e"},{"sha":"00d31f1d50c3ef475d8301f70ffbf0647038f53f","author":{"name":"Peter Hawkins","email":"34b19541630131950b5f204f2c5f2c647a3a7475@google.com"},"message":"[XLA] Fix interface contract of xla::LogDet.

xla::LogDet was previously mixing the sign of the determinant with the sign of the logarithm. These semantics don't make sense.

Create two methods: xla::SLogDet() which returns a (sign, determinant) pair, and xla::LogDet() which returns the log-determinant for matrices with positive determinant, and NaN otherwise.

The semantics of xla::LogDet() match torch.logdet, and PyTorch/XLA is the only user of this function at the moment.

[{"sha":"00d31f1d50c3ef475d8301f70ffbf0647038f53f","author":{"name":"Peter Hawkins","email":"34b19541630131950b5f204f2c5f2c647a3a7475@google.com"},"message":"[XLA] Fix interface contract of xla::LogDet.

xla::LogDet was previously mixing the sign of the determinant with the sign of the logarithm. These semantics don't make sense.

Create two methods: xla::SLogDet() which returns a (sign, determinant) pair, and xla::LogDet() which returns the log-determinant for matrices with positive determinant, and NaN otherwise.

The semantics of xla::LogDet() match torch.logdet, and PyTorch/XLA is the only user of this function at the moment.

Change-Id: I23c5b452869f772ad61a166253d1f6d4b4a508cc","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/kokizzu/tensorflow/commits/b6f149d84ca077d825c65e61f26d5308cac02d0c"},{"sha":"cb58fbae7070eab1a58a76ef26eb439b8ec34d6d","author":{"name":"Prakalp Srivastava","email":"7da1985d121fd79537822bb42be62798d2d2aa23@google.com"},"message":"Keep track of visited functions during export using a Set during MLIR to Graph export.

ConvertLibFunction checks if the requested function has already been exported by first creating a FunctionLibraryDefinition (map between function name and function def) and then querying it with function name. Since we immediately discard this FunctionLibraryDefinition, we incur the creation and destruction cost of FunctionLibraryDefinition each time we export a function. Using a set to keep track of visited functions is much less expensive.

xla::LogDet was previously mixing the sign of the determinant with the sign of the logarithm. These semantics don't make sense.

Create two methods: xla::SLogDet() which returns a (sign, determinant) pair, and xla::LogDet() which returns the log-determinant for matrices with positive determinant, and NaN otherwise.

The semantics of xla::LogDet() match torch.logdet, and PyTorch/XLA is the only user of this function at the moment.

Change-Id: I9dd09bbd31bfe83b8040d06f147690e314cf9aca","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/xiaoxiaopingzi/tensorflow/commits/7f8f4fe39bc1908e52ccb285f42fb60b7f380d7e"},{"sha":"00d31f1d50c3ef475d8301f70ffbf0647038f53f","author":{"name":"Peter Hawkins","email":"34b19541630131950b5f204f2c5f2c647a3a7475@google.com"},"message":"[XLA] Fix interface contract of xla::LogDet.

xla::LogDet was previously mixing the sign of the determinant with the sign of the logarithm. These semantics don't make sense.

Create two methods: xla::SLogDet() which returns a (sign, determinant) pair, and xla::LogDet() which returns the log-determinant for matrices with positive determinant, and NaN otherwise.

The semantics of xla::LogDet() match torch.logdet, and PyTorch/XLA is the only user of this function at the moment.

Before this change, a node prefix was added to all function names, for both functions originally from graphdef library and functions generated by the functionalize process. This is problematic if there are 2 signature_def using the same BatchFunction Op, which references to a same function from the graphdef library, because it would generate 2 copies of the same function and break the invariant in BatchFunction Op.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 360471859
Change-Id: I23c5b452869f772ad61a166253d1f6d4b4a508cc","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/xiaohanhuang/tensorflow/commits/b6f149d84ca077d825c65e61f26d5308cac02d0c"},{"sha":"cb58fbae7070eab1a58a76ef26eb439b8ec34d6d","author":{"name":"Prakalp Srivastava","email":"7da1985d121fd79537822bb42be62798d2d2aa23@google.com"},"message":"Keep track of visited functions during export using a Set during MLIR to Graph export.

ConvertLibFunction checks if the requested function has already been exported by first creating a FunctionLibraryDefinition (map between function name and function def) and then querying it with function name. Since we immediately discard this FunctionLibraryDefinition, we incur the creation and destruction cost of FunctionLibraryDefinition each time we export a function. Using a set to keep track of visited functions is much less expensive.
